title: Which Age Group is the Most Fit?
description: This project uses interactive visualizations of treadmill exercise data to show how athletic performance and physiological efficiency vary by age. By tracking VO₂, heart rate, and breathing rate, users can explore how different age groups respond to intense effort—and rethink what it truly means to be fit.

title: Boston Bikewatching
description: This project involves building an immersive and interactive map visualization of bike traffic in the Boston area. The map will display Boston's roads, neighborhoods, and bike lanes using datasets from the city governments of Boston and Cambridge.

title: How Do Students' Stress Fluctuate Throughout an Exam Period?
description: This project visualizes how students' stress levels change throughout different exams using interactive data representation. By tracking four stress indicators (e.g., heart rate, electrodermal activity) across midterms and finals, we allow users to explore stress trends in an engaging way.

title: An Analysis on the Relationship Between Recipe Complexity & Recipe Popularity
description: This project explores how recipe complexity relates to popularity using interactive data from Food.com. Users can see how longer recipes tend to get more reviews, revealing how complexity may influence what people cook and engage with online. Through data visualization, hypothesis testing, and predictive modeling, the project invites users to consider how complexity influences what people cook and review online.
